Prune public sublibs that no component in the package reaches.

Cabal's solver builds a single `flagged_deps` list per package that bundles
every component's dependencies, including public sublibraries.  If any
sublib has a `build-depends` entry that isn't in the repo, the whole
package fails to solve — even when the user only targets the main library.

Example: `vector-0.13.2.0` exposes a public `library benchmarks-O2` sublib
which `build-depends: tasty`.  Targeting `vector:lib:vector` with a
slicing repo that doesn't contain `tasty` makes the solver fail, because
the sublib is in `flagged_deps` regardless of whether it's reachable from
what we build.

This patch walks the intra-package dep graph from the main library and
every executable component, collects the sublibs they transitively
reference, and removes the rest from `flagged_deps`.  A sublib that no
local component reaches cannot contribute to the targeted build, so its
external deps don't need to be satisfiable.

Escape hatch: a slice that targets one of `pn`'s sublibs directly
(e.g. `:pkg:io-classes:lib:strict-stm`) needs that sublib to *stay* in
the index — pruning it would make cabal raise `[Cabal-7127]` "package
does not contain a library with that name" when it tries to resolve the
target.  The slice driver exports `HASKELLNIX_EXTRA_SUBLIB_SEEDS` (a
comma-separated list of `pkg/sublib` entries); each entry adds that
sublib as an extra reachability seed, so it (and its transitively-
required sublibs) survive pruning while unrelated sublibs (e.g.
`lib:testlib` with its QuickCheck dep) are still dropped.

Caveat: an external package's `build-depends: thispkg:lib:unusedsublib`
will still require that sublib's deps.  If that matters, a downstream
solve can reinstate them via the usual cabal mechanisms — this pruning
only affects the within-package solve.

